### Description

Currently, an `EnvironmentInjector` created with `createEnvironmentInjector(providers, parentInjector)` is not destroyed when its parent injector is destroyed.

This is intentional behavior, as child injectors are expected to manage their own lifecycle explicitly. However, this makes manually created child `EnvironmentInjector`s different from other Angular lifecycle-bound primitives such as effects/resources, which are automatically cleaned up with their parent injection context by default, unless the user explicitly opts into manual cleanup.

In many real-world cases, a child `EnvironmentInjector` is not an independent long-lived injector. It is created as a scoped child of the application/root injector and still depends on application-level providers. When the parent/application injector is destroyed, such a child injector may remain alive, but it is only partially usable: it can still resolve providers declared directly in the child injector, but resolving dependencies from the destroyed parent injector can fail with `NG0205`.

This can also leave cleanup registered through `DestroyRef.onDestroy()` inside child-provided services unexecuted unless the child injector is manually tracked and destroyed.

### Proposed solution

Add an option to `createEnvironmentInjector` that allows the child injector lifecycle to be bound to the parent injector lifecycle.

For example:

```ts
const injector = createEnvironmentInjector(providers, parentInjector, {
  manualCleanup: true,
});
```

- by default, a child `EnvironmentInjector` created from a parent injector is destroyed when the parent injector is destroyed;
- if a user intentionally wants the child injector to outlive its parent and only rely on its own local providers, they can opt into manual lifecycle management with `manualCleanup: true`;
- alternatively, to avoid any breaking change, Angular could keep the current default and add an explicit option such as `manualCleanup: false`.

### Alternatives considered

The current workaround is to manually register cleanup:

```ts
const injector = createEnvironmentInjector(providers, parentInjector);

injector.onDestroy(
  parentInjector.get(DestroyRef).onDestroy(() => {
    injector.destroy();
  }),
);
```

This works and also handles the case where the child injector is destroyed before the parent injector: in that case, the `onDestroy` callback registered on the parent `DestroyRef` is unregistered when the child injector is destroyed.

But, this ownership relationship has to be expressed manually by every user. It is also easy to forget, especially when the child injector is created as a scoped implementation detail and is expected to follow the parent/application lifecycle.

